Profit and debt dynamics

Total profits: \[ \Pi := p Y - w L - \delta_{\mathbf{D}^K} p K - r D + p \Upsilon \]

Profit share: \[ \pi := \frac{\Pi}{p Y} \]

Dividends: \[ \Pi_{d} := \Delta(\pi) p Y \]

where the dividend function \(\Delta(\pi)\) is given by

Retained earnings: \[ \Pi_{r} := \Pi - \Pi_{d} \]

Real investment:

\[ I := \kappa(\pi) Y \]

where the investment function \(\kappa(\pi)\) is given by one of the following (I am currently using the linear one):

Debt dynamics: \[ \dot{D} := p (I - \delta_{\mathbf{D}^K} K) - \Pi_{r} \]

Capital dynamics:

\[ \dot{K} := I - \delta_{\mathbf{D}^K} K \]

Exploring investment dynamics

I will explore the investment dynamics with three different scenarios. The scenarios are given by the following initial conditions:

IC_1 <- c(
  # Economic variables
  Y_N       =  30,       # global GDP, in trillions of USD
  d_N       =  1.5,      # private debt ratio of the economy
  lambda_N  =  0.67,     # employment rate of the global economy
  omega_N   =  0.58,     # wage share of the economy
  N_N       =  2.4,      # Workforce of the (world) economy, in billions /2
  g_sigma_N =  -0.0105,  # Growth rate of the emissions intensity of the economy
  n_N       =  0.03,     # Emissions reduction rate
  E_ind_N   =  18,       # Industrial CO2-e emissions, in Gt CO2-e
  
  # Climate variables - unchanged in all scenarios
  CO2_AT   =  851,      # CO2-e concentration in the atmosphere layer, in Gt C
  CO2_UP   =  460,      # CO2-e concentration in the biosphere and upper ocean layer, in Gt C
  CO2_LO   =  1740,     # CO2-e concentration in the deep ocean layer, in Gt C
  E_land   =  2.6,      # Exogenous land use change CO2-e emissions, in Gt CO2-e
  p        =  1,        # Composite good price level
  p_BS     =  547.22,   # Backstop technology price level
  Temp     =  0.85,     # Temperature in the atmosphere, biosphere, and upper ocean layer, in degrees Celsius
  Temp_LO  =  0.0068    # Temperature in the deep ocean layer, in degrees Celsius
)

# Set up simulation
Time <- c(
  start         =     2016, 
  end           =     2100,
  step          =     0.05, 
  start_p_Car_N =     2016
)

Active <- list(
  Damage_N     =   'None',       # None / Nordhaus / Weitzman / Stern
  Damage_K     =    0,           # Fraction of damages allocated to capital
  Temperature  =    TRUE,        # T / F
  Lab_Prod_N   =   'constant',   # constant / Burke
  p_Car_N      =   'None',       # None / Low / Medium / High / Canada
  s_A_N        =   0,            # fraction of abatement costs subsidized by government
  Phillips     =   'linear',     # linear / asymptotic
  Invest       =   'linear'      # linear / arctan
)

#================================================================================
## Run a scenario
# Initial conditions from Bovari et al. (2018) (Y=30, d=1.5, lambda=0.67, omega=0.58)
Simulation1 <- simulation(time             = Time,
                          init_sim         = IC_1,
                          pars             = Pars,
                          active           = Active,
                          method           = 'lsoda',
                          show_end_results = FALSE,
                          show_graph       = T
)

It is worth noting that with this specification the model doesn’t approach the bad equilibrium even with very poor initial conditions (ex. d=5, lambda=0.4, Y=5). This is true with both the linear and non-linear Phillips curve.

Linear investment curve - AFD

First, I use the linear investment specification from AFD (Bovari et al., 2018). The parameters for the investment curve are:

  ### Investment function
  # linear
  I_lin_constant = 0.0318,         # Bovari et al. (2018b)
  I_lin_slope    = 0.5753,         # Bovari et al. (2018b)
  I_lin_max      = 0.3,            # Bovari et al. (2018b)
  I_lin_min      = 0,              # Bovari et al. (2018b)

which gives the following investment curve:

What happens with investment in these scenarios? The plots below show the fraction of total profits invested (ie \(\frac{I}{\Pi}\)) for the three different scenarios.

Since investment is a function of the profit share, it is worth plotting the profit share (\(\pi = \frac{\Pi}{pY}\)) in each scenario.

Conclusion

Grasselli and Maheshwari (2017) estimated the capital accumulation rate for the Goodwin model for 10 OECD countries. The model is simpler, but somewhat similarly to our model it is assumed that a fraction \(k\) of profits are re-invested while the remaining \((1-k)\) are paid out as profits. \(k\) is estimated by dividing gross capital formation by profits. Grasselli and Maheshwari estumate \(k\) to be in the range of 0.605 to 0.898, so much higher than what the model gives now, no matter the specification of investment function (including ones not shown above). Right now investment equilibrates at about 20% of profits.
